# Chat Graph Interaction Stability Rule

For chat-first graph UX, preserve interaction quality and avoid regression loops.

## 1. Never let typing move the graph

- Typing in chat inputs, textareas, and contenteditable controls must not trigger Cytoscape movement or relayout.
- Keep keyboard events scoped to editable controls.
- Do not rely on broad interaction disablement (for example turning off drag/zoom/pan) as a workaround.

## 2. Preserve core graph interactions

- Node dragging must remain enabled.
- Mouse zoom and pan must remain enabled unless the user explicitly asks to disable them.
- If keyboard handling is adjusted, verify mouse interactions still work end-to-end.

## 3. Avoid relayout churn from unrelated React renders

- Do not pass newly allocated props (for example `new Set()` or new object literals) each render when values are logically static.
- Memoize static references and avoid triggering Cytoscape re-sync on chat-input updates.
- Relayout should run when graph data changes, not when unrelated UI state changes.

## 4. Validation expectation

- After graph interaction changes, validate this workflow on `http://localhost:3000`:
  1. Type in chat input continuously.
  2. Confirm graph viewport and node positions remain stable.
  3. Drag a node with mouse.
  4. Zoom and pan with mouse.

